urls.title: Connecting to databases
urls.description: Observable database clients allow secure and convenient querying of SQL databases from private notebooks. You can feed query results directly into visualizations, and you can use reactive values as parameters in dynamic queries! This walkthrough discusses connecting notebooks to databases that are reachable from the public internet, with the connection hosted by Observable. If you wish to use your notebooks to q

urls.description: A collection of snippets for working with arrays, math, randomness, animation and geometry. Elements going out of the array are added at the opposite end/beginning of the array. shuffle non

In Observable, evaluation is orthogonal to document order ‚Äî so, in the minimap, they‚Äôre literally perpendicular. However you arrange your cells top-to-bottom, the left-to-right wiring stays the same. https://t.co/KMwycuaBiM

Dependency graphs are tricky:

‚ë† They‚Äôre overwhelming ‚Äî so we show only direct dependencies (plus hints of transitive ones). 

‚ë° They‚Äôre underconstrained ‚Äî so we use your chosen document order as a meaningful vertical position. https://t.co/EzKx4R40oi
We‚Äôre inspired by minimaps like Sublime‚Äôs, but wanted to try something more adapted to Observable: instead of miniature lines of text, we show dependencies. Runtime behavior, not raw source code.

Second, we‚Äôve added a minimap to the right edge of the screen, showing every cell‚Äôs name and runtime state: running, idle, or errored. When focused, a cell lights up and shows which other cells it depends on, and which depend on it. https://t.co/o5jPvKXdf7

First, syntax highlighting now distinguishes cell references from normal JavaScript references. Hit ‚åòCmd-J on Mac or Ctrl-J on PC to jump to the referenced cell‚Äôs definition. Cell references behave differently (they‚Äôre reactive!), and now we‚Äôre showing that. https://t.co/Dhwox3SuU6

Reactivity is awesome, intimidating, and confusing. It‚Äôs fundamental to Observable but we haven‚Äôt made it clear or obvious. We‚Äôre part notebook, part spreadsheet, and we should help people see that. Like, I mean, SEE it. So we‚Äôre launching Visual Dataflow: https://t.co/uyYddUyGNg https://t.co/mv5Q7pbs3O

urls.description: The Observable dataflow runtime. Contribute to observablehq/runtime development by creating an account on GitHub.

tweets.text: This JavaScript runs in the context of your page, so your JavaScript can interact with it! With the open source Observable runtime you can react to changes or push new event and data in. https://t.co/lEHJ2KiRb2
You can embed Observable notebooks, as individual cells or whole notebooks, in other websites. Here's an example of embedding a single cell with Flask: https://t.co/QEO8Oj2Lqv

Read the notebook linked above for more detail on all of these! The next in the series goes over embedding visualizations in Jupyter:
https://t.co/hCupWJjOMZ

If you want to embed custom, dynamic visualizations written in JavaScript into Jupyter notebooks, check out how to get data into Observable and get a chart back into Jupyter:

https://t.co/C3fOhKYQME

7. Execution happens in your browser.

This is very different from using a remote kernel! Notebooks boot instantly (no queueing for Docker containers to boot etc.) and latency is much lower, but you miss things too: no more shelling out to bash, no more accessing your local FS.

6. You can import from other notebooks.

Similar to solutions for Jupyter like adding a module loader to the meta_path in Python, in Observable cells can be imported from other notebooks.

5. There's just one kind of cell.

In Jupyter, markdown cells have metadata designating them so, but in Observable this happens at runtime. This makes dynamically changing markdown simple! https://t.co/a5wjaRbXjl

4. An implication of reactivity: Cells can be out of (execution) order!

Since execution doesn't flow from top to bottom, authors order cells to make notebooks easier to understand. This means that if you want, the final result can be the first thing readers see!

3. Cell output is shown *above* the code.

This works well because cell outputs are always shown while code can be hidden, but it can be jarring at first!

2. The big one: notebooks are reactive!

Cells that depend on other cells update automatically. https://t.co/8poS8znkVn
